column168: RECEIVED A CALL FROM DAN DYER AT 4:00, HE TOLD ME HE HAD A CORROSIVE SPILL.  I REVIEWED THE DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEETS BEFORE RESPONDING.  I PUT ON PROPER PPE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL TO A PH OF 7.  BROUGHT THE SPILL BACK TO THE PSC AND PROCESSED IT THROUGH THE DMP PROCEDURE.

column168: AT 2350 DMP AREA WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING CORROSIVE PARCEL.  AFTER CONSULTING DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, I THEN PROCEEDED TO SOUT SORT TWO.  WHILE WEARING APRON, BOOTS, GLOVES, GOGGLES I PLACED THE LEAKER IN A SPILL TUB OF SODIUM BICARBONATE.  PH READING WAS AROUND 12.  ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED TO A PH OF 7.  BACK AT DMP AREA ALL MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM. CONTENTS WERE RETURNED.

AT 0535 HOURS I WAS CALLED TO A 5-PART CORROSIVE SPILL IN DOOR #38 IN PRIMARY.  ON ARRIVAL I PUT ON PROPER PPE.  VIEWING DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID I TOOK PH READING AND FOUND IT TO BE PH 13.  SPRINKLING SODIUM BICARBONATE I SWEPT UP SUBSTANCE AND CONTAINERIZED WET PACKAGE.  THIS PACKAGE WAS THEN BROUGHT TO DMP FOR PROCESSING.

OUR DRIVER WAS LOADING A LOAD OF CRUDE OIL FROM A STORAGE TANK, THAT SHOULD HAVE BEEN EASILY HELD BY HIS TRAILER. WHEN IT OVER FLOWED FROM HIS VENT LINE, HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT EVERYTHING DOWN, LIMITING HIS SPILL TO 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT. UPON INVESTIGATION, HE FOUND THE VALVE TO THE SECOND TANK TO BE OPEN WHICH WAS CONNECTED TO THE SAME LOAD LINE AS THE TANK HE WAS LOADING. THIS TANK HAD BEEN LEFT OPEN AND UNSEALED, BUT THE HANDLE WAS IN THE LOCKING POSITION. WE ARE IN THE PROCESS OF INSTALLING OVER FLOW PROTECTORS ALL OF OUR TRAILERS. ALSO THE DRIVER NEEDS TO INSPECT EACH VALVE BEFORE LOADING.

THE DRIVER HAD UNLOADED APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS WHEN THE TANK FILLED AND OVERFLOWED.  THE HAZMAT TEAM WAS AGAIN CALLED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  THE ESCORT FINALLY LOCATED A TANK THAT WOULD HOLD THE LOAD.

PER MY RESPONSE SHEETS, I USED SOLUSORB TO BE METHANOL, A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  PER MY RESPONSE SHEETS, I USED SOLUSORB AND CLAY ABSORBANT TO SOAK UP THE SPILL. AFTER READING THE RESPONSE SHEETS ABSORBED UP REMAINING LIQUID AND TRANSFERRED THE LIQUID INTO NEW CONTAINERS AND PLACED THE PROPER MARKINGS ON THE NEW CONTAINER AND RESHIPPED THEM.

ONE OF THE METAL FEET OF THE DRUM DOLLY STRUCK THE LOWER SIDE OF THE DRUM NEAR THE BOTTOM CAUSING A SMALL PUNCTURE.  DRUM TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. ONE, 55 GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT.  RICHARD PARKER WAS LAYING DRUM ON ITS SIDE WHEN A SMALL AMOUNT SPLASHED IN HIS EYES.  HE WAS TAKEN TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM WHERE CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.  THE DOCTOR WASHED RICHARDS EYES OUT AND WAS SENT HOME, WITH NO FURTHER COMPLICATIONS.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SENT BACK TO SHIPPER PER THE SHIPPER.  ATTENTION:  GARLENE WORKMAN.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM RURAL ELECTRIC COMPANY LOCATED AT 6270 COUNTRY RD IN PINE BLUFFS, WY TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATLEY ONE PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED AT THE MIDDLE CHIME OF THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 1-2 OUNCES ESCAPED FROM THE VEHICLE ONTO THE CONCRETE CONTAIMENT OFF-LOADING AREA OF THE FACILITY. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS EVENT WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: A DUMP TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM LAGLORIA OIL & GAS COMPANY LOCATED AT 1702 EAST COMMERCE ST IN TYLER, TX TO CLEAN HARBORS TECHNOLOGY CORPORATION LOCATED 5 MILES SOUTH OF KIMBALL ON HIGHWAY 71 IN KIMBALL, NE.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP TO CONDUCT A TIRE AND LOAD CHECK.  DURING THIS INSPECTION, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE REAR DOOR OF THE DUMP TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRI.  THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE DUMP TRAILER AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER DOCUMENT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE DRUM TRAILER INDICATED THAT 2 OF THE CLOSURE DEVICES LOCATED ON THE REAR DOOR HAD BROKEN OFF ALLOWING THE SEAL TO BE BROKEN AT THE BACK DOOR ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE.  THE DRIVER'S SUPERVISOR DISPATCHED ANOTHER DRIVER TO THE SCENE EQUIPPED WITH CHAINS AND BINDERS WHICH WERE USED TO SECURE THE BACK DOOR AND REGAIN THE SEAL BETWEEN THE DOOR AND THE TRAILERS BODY. ONCE SECURED, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO HIS INTENDED DESTINATION WHERE THE SHIPMENT WAS OFF-LOADED AND THE VEHICLE REPAIRED.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE VEHICLE WAS INSPECTED AND ALL CLOSURE DEVICES WERE PRESENT AND IN WORKING ORDER.  DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT THEIR VEHICLES ON BOTH A PRE AND POST TRIP BASIS AND CORRECT ANY DEFICIENCIES DISCOVERED PRIOR TO MOVING THE VEHICLE.

AS CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS WERE CONTINUING A SECOND EVACUATION WAS ORDERED FOR ANOTHER 48 HOURS DUE TO VAPOR BUILD-UP AND FIRE AND EXPLOSION RISKS.  ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION EFFORTS CONTINUE.  RAIL OPERATIONS REMAIN CURTAILED.  THE NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY BOARD IS CONDUCTING AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE CAUSE OF THE TANK FAILURE.  THE FEDERAL ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY IS COORDINATING THE CLEANUP EFFORTS.  NEWS PHOTOS ATTACHED.

column168: TWELVE 4BW240 CARBON STEEL CYLINDERS WERE SHIPPED IN A EXPORT BOX CONTAINER FOR SURFACE TRANSPORT TO INDIA.  A RED LIQUID WAS DETECTED AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER AT THE CARRIER TERMINAL IN CALIFORNIA.  GREAT LAKES CHEMICAL, EL DORADO WAS CONTACCTED AND A HAZMAT TEAM WAS SENT TO THE SITE.  THE TEAM WITH HELP FROM LOCAL CONTRACTORS REMOVED THE LEAKING CYLINDER AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE OTHER CYLINDERS WERE CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.  THE OTHER CYLINDER THAT LEAKED WAS TAKEN TO GREAT LAKES FACILITY IN MCFARLAND, CALIFORNIA.  THE OTHER CYLINDERS WERE RETURNED TO GREAT LAKES IN EL DORADO, ARKANSAS.  THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE AT A SPOT WELD THAT ATTACHED THE FOOT RING TO THE CYLINDER.  INITIAL INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT THE SPOT WELD PENETRATED TOO DEEP AND WAS THE REASON FOR THE METAL FAILURE.  A JOINT INVESTIGATION BY THE MANUFACTURER AND GREAT LAKES CHEMICAL PERSONNEL IS UNDER WAS TO MAKE CHANGES TO PREVENT FURTHER FAILURES OF THIS KIND.
REPORTED TO AREA WITH SPILL CART.  DONNED PPE & USED FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  NO UNABSORBED LIQUID WAS PRESENT.  PLACED DAMAGED MATERIAL IN PLASTIC BAG AND DISPOSED THROUGH DMP PROCESS.

OUR PLANT FOREMAN MADE UP LOADING INSTRUCTIONS TO LOAD A CARGO TANK.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO LOAD THIS TRAILER.  HOWEVER, DURING THE LOADING PROCESS HE WAS PULLED AWAY AND HAD ANOTHER EMPLOYEE TAKE OVER FOR HIM.  THE PERSON WHO TOOK OVER THE LOADING PROCESS DID NOT READ THE LOADING INSTRUCTIONS CORRECTLY.  THIS RESULTED IN HIS TRYING TO LOAD 1000 GALLONS INTO A 550 GALLON COMPARTMENT.  THERE WERE TWO CONTRIBUTING FACTORS.  THE FIRST WAS THE MANNER IN WHICH THE LOADING INSTRUCTIONS WERE COMPLETED.  THE SECOND WAS POOR COMMUNICATION BETWEEN THE TWO PERSONS INVOLVED.  CORRECTIVE ACTION INCLUDES CLARIFYING THE LOADING INSTRUCTIONS AND TRAINING TO EMPHASIZE THE IMPORTANCE OF BETTER COMMUNICATION BETWEEN TWO PERSON WHEN JOB DUTIES ARE BEING TRANSFERRED.

column168: THE FOLLOWING IS THE INITIAL REPORT OF THE ACCIDENT ON 2-1-96 THAT OCCURRED AT M.P. 18, U.S. HIGHWAY 70 STATE OF NEW MEXICO.  THE ACCIDENT INVOLVED A C.M.V. UNITS. UNIT 1 WAS A STEERE TANK LINES UNIT HAULING DIESEL FUEL TRAVELING WEST ON HIGHWAY 70.  UNIT 1 WAS STEERE TANK LINES UNIT HAULING DIESEL FUL TRAVELING WEST ON HIGHWAY 70.  UNIT 2 AS A B.J. CECIL TRUCKING, INC. UNIT HAULING SULFURIC ACID ALSO TRAVELING WEST ON HIGHWAY 70.  THE DRIVER OF UNIT (1) REPORTED THAT HIS LIGHTS WENT OUT WHILE HE WAS IN ROUTE.  THE WEATHER WAS HEAVY RAIN AND SOME FOG ON THE ROADWAY AS WELL AS LARGE AMOUNTS OF WATER PUDDLES IN THE LOW AREA OF THE HIGHWAY.  THE MARKS LEFT BY UNIT(1) INDICATE IT TRAVELED OFF THE RIGHT HAND SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY ONTO THE SOFT RAIN SOAKED SHOULDER AND THEN TRAVELED ABOUT 150 FEET BEFORE RETURNING BACK TOWARD THE PAVED PORTION WHERE IT ROLLED CLOSING OFF THE ENTIRE WEST BOUND LANE AND APPROXIMATELY 2/3 OF THE EAST BOUND LANE.  THERE WAS A RELEASE OF A QUANTITY OF DIESEL FUEL ONTO THE HIGHWAY IN THE WEST BOUND LANE ABOUT 75 FEET LONG JUST EAST OF WHERE UNIT (1) CAME TO REST.  THERE WERE NO LIGHTS WORKING ON UNIT (1) CAME TO REST.  THERE WAS A PRIVATE AUTOMOBILE AT THE SCENE WHEN UNIT (2), (B.J. CECIL TRUCKING, INC. #20) APPROACHED THE AREA.  IT IS UNCLEAR AS TO WHERE THE AUTOMOBILE WAS WITH RESPECT TO UNIT (1) BUT IT WAS SHINING ITS BRIGHT LIGHTS TOWARD THE EAST MAKING IT DIFFICULT TO SEE PAST THE AUTOMOBILE. WHEN UNIT (2) PASSED THE AUTOMOBILE THE DRIVER SAW THE BOTTOM SIDE OF UNIT (1) JUST FRONT OF HIM, HE IMMEDIATELY TURNED TO THE LEFT TO AVOID HITTING THE TANKER IN THE MIDDLE (THE DRIVER RECOGNIZED THAT IT WAS A TANKER FROM THE DELIVERY VALVES AND ASSOCIATED PIPING FOR UNLOADING THE UNIT.)  THE TIRES INDICATE THAT UNIT (2) HAD ITS BRAKES LOCKED, (FROM THE AMOUNT OF RUBBER SKIDDED OFF THE TIRES) AT THE TIME OF IMPACT WITH UNIT (1) SINCE THE FLAT SPOTS WERE ON THE BOTTOM OF WHERE THE TIRES WERE CONTACTING THE ROAD.  (THERE WASN'T ANY WHEEL ROTATION AFTER IMPACT AS INDICATED BY THE WHEEL POSITION AND TIRE FLAT SPOTS).  INDICATIONS ARE THAT UNIT(2) IMPACTED UNIT (1) IN THE CENTER OF THE CAB AREA.  THE DRIVER UNIT(1) WAS OUT OF HIS TRUCK AND AT THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WHEN THE IMPACT OCCURRED, ACCORDING TO VERBAL REPORTS AT THE SCENE TAKEN LATER IN THE DAY. THE DRIVER OF UNIT (1) HELPED THE DRIVER OF UNIT (2) OUT OF THE CRUMPLED CAB ON UNIT (2) AS THE IMPACT TURNED UNIT (2) ON ITS LEFT SIDE WHERE IT SLID APPROXIMATELY 60 FEET RESTING IN THE BAR PIT WITH THE END OF THE TRAILER ON THE PAVED SHOULDER APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET FROM THE EDGE OF THE PAVED PORTION.  UNIT (2) ON ITS LEFT SIDE WHERE IT SLID APPROXIMATELY 60 FEET RESTING IN THE BAR PIT WITH THE END OF THE TRAILER ON THE PAVE SHOULDER APPROXIMATLEY 4 FEET RESTING IN THE BAR PIT WITH THE END OF THE TRAILER ON THE PAVED SHOULDER APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET FROM THE EDGE OF THE PAVED PORTION. column168: OUR DRIVER HOOKED UP TO TANK, CHECKED WITH SYSTEM OPERATOR AND PROCEEDED TO BLOW OFF PRODUCT.  OUR DRIVER CHECKED TANK SIGHT GLASS AND HE ASKED IF THE SIGHT GLASS AND HE ASKED IF THE SIGHT GLASS WAS OPERABLE AND WAS INFORMED BY SYSTEM OPERATOR THAT IT WAS.  DRIVER THEN CHECKED THE TRUCK GAUGES TO SEE IF PRODUCT WAS FLOWING, AND 10 MINUTES LATER THE SPILL OCCURED DUE TO OVERFLOW.  DRIVER SHUT OFF VALVES TO STOP FLOW OF PRODUCT. THE CONSIGNEES TANK HAD MORE PRODUCT IN IT THAN THEY ESTIMATED.  THERE WAS AN IN-HOUSE DRAINAGE SYSTEM, SO THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE STORAGE TANK AREA.

TO THE BEST OF OUR KNOWLEDGE, DUE TO EXTREME TEMPERATURE CPVC PIPING IN A TRANSFER SYSTEM BECAME BRITTLE AND FAILED.  THE PIPING TRANSFERS HCL TO A TRUCK LOADING FACILITY.  FAILURE OF PIPING RELEASED THE CONTENTS FROM 5 STORAGE TANKS WITH 30,000 GALLON CAPACITIES.  THE TANKS WERE NOT FULL AND DID NOT FAIL.  ALMOST ALL THE RELEASE WAS TRANSFERRED INTO RAIL CARS AND TRUCKS AND USED.  THE BALANCE THE COULD NOT BE LOADED WAS NEUTRALIZED. THE TWO MINOR INJURIES WERE DUE TO HCL FUMES.  INJURED CONTINUED TO WORK. TO DATE, ALL THE RELATED COSTS ARE NOT KNOWN.

column168: DRIVER OVERFILLED THE MID-GRADE TANK RESULTING IN A TEN GALLON SPILL WHEN THE FITTING CONNECTION GAVE WAY.

2/22/96 - AFTER OUR DRIVER GOT THE OK TO UNLOAD, HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO OPEN THE CONSIGNEE'S VALVE 1/2 WAY AND HE OPENED VALVE ON CARGO AND AIRED UP TANK.  UNLOADER CAME BACK AND SAID PRODUCT WAS NOT FLOWING INTO STORAGE TANK.  HE WANTED MORE AIR PRESSURE.  OUR DRIVER TOLD HIM TO GO AND CHECK AGAIN.  AFTER CHECKING UNLOADING HOSE, WHICH DRIVER FELT PRODUCT WAS FLOWING, UNLOADER CAME BACK AND SAID ITS FLOWING.  ABOUT 30 MINUTES LATER, HOSE STARTED TO JUMP AND UNLOADER CAME OUT AND MOTIONED TO CUT PRODUCT OFF, WHICH OUR DRIVER ALREADY DID,  UNHOOKED HOSES AND WENT INSIDE TO GET BILLS SIGNED.  FIRST UNLOADER WAS WASHING DOWN FOAM INTO SEWER THAT LEADS INTO THE TREATMENT PLANT.  DRIVER HAD ASKED IF PRODUCT HAD FOAMED OUT OF VENT.  HE SAID YES.  DRIVER ASKED IF UNLOADER NEED HELP AND UNLOADER SAID NO.  HE HAD EVERYTHING UNDER CONTROL.  DRIVER STATED THAT IT DIDN'T LOOK LIKE VERY MUCH FOAM HAD SPILLED OVER.  THE NEXT DAY WE RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE SHIPPER ASKING IF WE COULD MAKE RECOMMENDATIONS TO LESSEN THE OVERFLOW OF FOAM.  THAT'S WHEN WE FOUND OUT THE CONSIGNEE LOST 14,000 LBS. WE DELIVERED 29,060 LBS INTO A 1/4 FILLED 80,000 LBS.  STORAGE TANK.  ON 2/23/96 WE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED NATION RESPONSE CENTER, INCIDENT #327756 AND REPORTED LOSS OF PREVIOUS DAY.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: MTPL A -- THIS PRODUCT RELEASE WAS A CONSEQUENCE OF A DERAILMENT CAUSED BY FAILURE OF THE TRAIN'S AIR BRAKE SYSTEM.  THE FINAL DETERMINATION OF THE CAUSE OF THE BRAKE FAILURE REMAINS UNDER INVESTIGATION BY THE NTSB, FRA AND CALIFORNIA PUC. THE TRAIN ARRIVED AT THE SUMMIT OF CAJON PASS AND, AFTER STOPPING FOR A TRAIN AHEAD TO CLEAR, BEGAN DESCENDING THE STEEP 3.0% GRADE. SHORTLY AFTER DEPARTING THE SUMMIT, THE CREW REPORTED THAT THE TRAIN BRAKES WERE INEFFECTIVE IN SLOWING THE TRAIN AND THAT THE TRAIN SHOULD BE CONSIDERED AS A RUNAWAY.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE MILES BEYOND THIS LOCATION, THE TRAIN DERAILED IN A CURVE. THE FOUR LOCOMOTIVES AND THE LEAD 45 CARS OF THE 49 CAR TRAIN WERE INVOLVED, INCLUDING THREE TANK CARS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. .............................. FIRE ERUPTED FOLLOWING A REPORTED EXPLOSION. ALTHOUGH THREE CARS OF FLAMMABLE AND COMBUSTIBLE REGULATED PRODUCTS WERE INVOLVED, THE PRIMARY FUEL SOURCES FOR THE FIRE WERE NON-REGULATED PRODUCTS SUCH AS PARTICLE BOARD, TIRES AND PLASTIC PELLETS. AN ESTIMATED TEMPERATURE OF 1600 TO 1800 DEGREES (F) WAS PROFFERED FOR THE ENSUING FIRE. .............................. DUE TO THE RESULTING DENSE SMOKE, INTERSTATE 15 AND CALIFORNIA STATE HIGHWAY 138 WERE CLOSED FOR MUCH OF THE FIVE DAY PERIOD. IN ADDITION, THE SECOND BNSF RAIL ROUTE AND THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAIL ROUTE WERE CLOSED DURING THE SAME TIME PERIODS AS THE HIGHWAYS. THE EVACUATION LASTED THROUGHOUT THE ASSESSMENT AND CLEARING ACTIVITIES. .............................. PRODUCT WAS RELEASED DUE TO IMPACT STRUCTURAL FAILURE OF THE TANK CAR, WITH MOST, IF NOT ALL, OF THE PRODUCT CONSUMED IN THE FIRE. A REMEDIATION PLAN PLUS AIR, SOIL AND WATER MONITORING WAS DEVELOPED AND APPROVED BY THE INVOLVED AGENCIES. THIS EFFORT IS CONTINUING. THE ESTIMATED INJURIES ARE BASED ON CLAIMS RECEIVED AS OF THIS DATE. .............................. MTPL B -- THIS CAR WAS REMOVED FROM THE BURNING WRECKAGE ON THE EVENING OF THE THIRD DAY (2/4 AT 2200 PT). IT HAD MAINTAINED ITS INTEGRITY DESPITE THE HIGH TEMPERATURE OF THE FIRE. SEVERAL HOURS AFTER REMOVAL, THE SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM (ALREADY ON THE SITE) HEARD A PERCOLATING NOISE WITHIN THE CAR THAT COULD INDICATE POLYMERIZATION WAS OCCURRING. THE AREA WAS EVACUATED AND ISOLATED. A PLAN WAS DEVELOPED TO BREACH THE CAR WITH SHAPED EXPLOSIVE CHARGES. THESE WERE PLACED AT OPPOSITE ENDS OF THE CAR. FOLLOWING DETONATION, APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED, BUT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN A BERMED AREA. THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT HAD REACTED WITHIN THE CAR. SATISFIED THAT THE CAR WAS NO LONGER A THREAT OF CATASTROPHIC FAILURE DUE TO RUNAWAY POLYMERIZATION, THE INCIDENT COMMANDER PERMITTED REOPENING OF THE AREA AT 2235 PT ON 2/5. .............................. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE SHIPPER HAS OPTED TO PACKAGE THIS PRODUCT IN A HIGH PRESSURE TANK CAR RATHER THAN THE MINIMUM SPECIFICATION LOW PRESSURE CAR. THE DOT 105 CAR OFFERS A SIGNIFICANTLY IMPROVED PACKAGE OVER THE DOT 111 CAR. A 75 POUND SAF

THE LID TO A 55 GALLON FIBER CONTAINER OF FIXER SOLUTION (IMAGINING WASTE) CAME LOOSE WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS BEING OFF LOADED FROM A TRUCK. APPROXIMATELY 3 GALS. OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO CONCRETE AT THE FACILITY.  NONE OF IT IMPACTED SOIL OR WATER.  ALL OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY WITH ABSORBENT.  TO PREVENT SIMILAR OCCURRENCES IN THE FUTURE, THE FACILITY WILL NO LONGER PICK UP FIBER CONTAINERS OF LIQUID IMAGING WASTE.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HOURS, TUESDAY, FEBRUARY 13, 1996, TANK CAR UTLX 83273 (RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINING PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED) WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AUDIT CONDUCTED BY CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM PERSONNEL AT THE CONRAIL BUCKEYE RAIL YARD FACILITY COLUMBUS, OH.  APPROXIMATE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE.  INSPECTION BY  CONRAIL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PERSONNEL REVEALED A LEAK AT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE O-RING ASSEMBLY AND A SMALL  LEAK AT THE BASE OF THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE WHERE IT THREADS INTO THE PRESSURE PLATE.  PERSONNEL (O H MATERIALS) RESPONDED TO THE RAIL YARD AND MADE NECESSARY REPAIRS AT APPROXIMATELY 1550 HOURS ON 2/14/96.  CAR RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HOURS.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: DURING THE SORT, WHITE POWDER BEGAN SIFTING THRU THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. WE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THAT THE EXTINGUISHER HAD DISCHARGED.  THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT ON TO THE RECIPIENT.

THE BOX WAS DROPPED DURING THE SORT AND UPON IMPACT WITH THE CEMENT FLOOR, CRACKED THE BOTTLE.  THERE WAS A TOTAL LOSS OF MATERIAL FROM THAT ONE BOTTLE.  THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER, WHEN NOTIFIED ADVISED US TO RETURN THE SHIPMENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: DURING THE SORT THIS PACKAGE BEGAN GIVING OFF A STRONG GASOLINE LIKE AROMA.  THE BOX WAS OPENED AND WE FOUND A CONTROL UNIT THAT HAD NOT BEEN DRAINED & PURGED.  IT APPEARED THAT ABOUT A PINT OF GASOLINE HAD LEAKED OUT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, OR SHIPPING PAPERS WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPPER & FAA HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED.  THE FREIGHT WILL BE HELD FOR AN FAA INSPECTION.
RESPONDED WITH FULL PPE ON SORT ISLE BELT, FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, PH13, NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE.  CONTROLLED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH DMP.

LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PARCEL FOUND IN BACK OF PACKAGE CAR BY DRIVER. RESPONDER NOTIFIED.  AREA CLEARED, RESPONDER IDENTIFIED, REMOVED, AND CLEANED UP HAZMAT ACCORDING TO THE DECISION TREE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET AND THE HAZMAT RESPONSE PROCEDURES.  DISPOSED OF WASTE THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.  RECOMMENDATIONS:  1.  LIQUID MATERIALS THAT ARE ENCLOSED BY GLASS BOTTLES SHOULD BE BAGGED, 2. PARCEL NEEDED MORE INNER CUSHIONING.  ACTION TAKEN:  SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF RECOMMENDATIONS.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: REMOVED THE LEAKER TO A PROCESSING AREA WHERE THE CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND REMOVED THE PACKAGES AND THE BOTTLES REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE CONTAMINATD MATERIALS WERE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF USING THE UP DMP PROGRAM.

I RESPONDED TO SPILL ON DOOR 5 OF THE UNLOAD.  IT TURNED OUT TO BE A FLAMMABLE HAZARD.  I USED THE FLAMMABLE SECTION OF THE RESPONSE SHEET TO PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE WASTE AND THE REST WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON DOOR #13.  RESPONDED TO SPILL USING FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  USING SPEEDY DRY TO ABSORB SPILL ACCORDING TO RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  DISPOSED OF MATERIAL ACCORDING TO DMP PROCEDURES.

DAMAGE PACKAGE CONTAINED FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS.  ONLY ONE GALLON WAS DAMAGED AS A RESULT OF A SMALL LEAK AT SEAM.  I USED THE LIQUID CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  I NEUTRALIZED THE SUBSTANCE WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE.  I DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL ACCORDING TO DMP PROCEDURE.

THE DAMAGE PACKAGE CONTAINED TWELVE, ONE QUART BOTTLES.  ONE BOTTLE WAS DAMAGED DUE TO LOOSE CAP.  I USED THE LIQUID CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  I NEUTRALIZED THE SUBSTANCE WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE.  I DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL ACCORDING TO DMP PROCEDURE.

I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON DOOR 53 OF THE LOAD.  I THEN NEUTRALIZED THE LIQUID AND ABSORBED WITH CLAY BASED ABSORBENT.  I USED PPE AND SPILL CART TO BRING PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA.  THE SOILED CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A DMP BAG AND PROCESSED ACCORDING TO DMP PROCEDURES.  THE REMAINDER WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A PACKAGE THAT WAS LABELED FLAMMABLE LIQUID. WHEN I GOT THERE WEARING MY PPE I COULD NOT SEE ANY SPILLAGE.  I TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP CAGE WHERE, I EXAMINED IT CLOSER.  I NOTICED THE PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED, MY DECISION TREE LEAD ME TO RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  I PROCESSED THE PACKAGE ACCORDING TO THE DMP PROCEDURE.

DRIVER WAS PERFORMING PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PRIOR TO LEAVING TERMINAL.  UPON INSPECTING THE LOAD,  HE NOTICED A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON FLOOR OF TRAILER.  ONE DRUM HAD FROZE AND SOME PRODUCT HAD SEEPED OUT OF THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  DRIVER CLEANED PRODUCT OFF FLOOR OF TRAILER AND DRUM WAS MONITORED FOR SEEPAGE.  NONE WAS DETECTED, THE TRAILER HAS SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.
WHILE DELIVERING THE FREIGHT, THE CITY DRIVER DISCOVERED ONE DRUM FROM THE BUNG OF THE DRUM.  THE CONSIGNEE TIGHTENED THE BUNG, NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL AND ACCEPTED THE DRUM.
CARTON WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM AS THE CARTON WAS PITTED.  MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, DISCOVERED A PAIL SEEPING FROM A FAULTY BUNG. THE SPILLAGE POOLED ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE SPILLAGE WAS ABSORBED AND NEUTRALIZED WITH PH-9.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  THE DOCKWORKER RECEIVED SUPERFICIAL BURNS ON HIS HANDS AND WENT TO THE CLINIC AND WAS TREATED AND RELATED.  THE DOCKWORKER MISSED ONE DAY OF WORK.

column42: PESTICIDES, LIQUID, TOXIC, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S. FLASH POINT NOT LESS THAN 23 DEGREES C
column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, ONE 2.5 GALLON CAN OF PESTICIDE WAS DISCOVERED CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT AND LEAKING.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, A FIBERBOARD DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM HEAD.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE RECOVERY DRUM AFTER BEING PATCHED.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, THE CORNER OF THE FORKLIFT WAS MAST CAUGHT THE LOWER PORTION OF A METAL PAIL OF NAPHTHA.  THE PAIL WAS OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE RECOVERY DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

THE RAILWAY DISPATCHING CENTER WAS NOTIFIED BY THE SHERMAN COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT CENTER OF A LARGE AMMONIA RELEASE IN STRAFORD.  RAIL TRAFFIC WAS HELD AND ROUTINE NOTIFICATION PROCEDURES WERE IMPLEMENTED TO STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES.  A TEAM OF RAILWAY HAZ MAT RESPONDERS WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE.  IN ADDITION, CHEMTREC WAS ASKED TO ACTIVATE THEIR MUTUAL AID SYSTEM TO MOBILIZE A TEAM OF HAZMAT RESPONDERS FROM PHILLIPS 66 AT BORGER.  THE RELEASE RESULTED FROM SEVERED PIPING ON STATIONARY STORAGE TANK AND THE PUMPING APPARATUS.  A NEW 7000 GALLONS PORTABLE STORAGE TANK HAD BEEN PLACED AT THE UNLOADING FACILITY. IT WAS SUPPORTED BY TWO CONCRETE CRADLES, EACH PLACED AT THE END OF A SKID-LIKE FRAME.  THIS WAS THE FIRST TRANSFER FROM A RAIL CAR INTO THE NEW TANK.  APPARENTLY THE WEIGHT OF THE PRODUCT FILLING THE TANK CAUSED THE SKID FRAME TO BUCKLE ACCOUNT SPACING OF THE CRADLES.  WHEN THE FRAME BICKLED, IT DEFORMED THE RIGID PIPING BETWEEN THE TWO TANKS, PUMPED AND RAIL CAR.  THEIS RESULTED IN SEVERED PIPES AND PERMITTED RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT ALREADY IN THE NEW TANK.  FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR CEASED DUE TO THE EXCESS FLOW CHECK VALVES INCLUDED IN THE CAR'S DESIGN; HOWEVER, VALVES HAD TO BE CLOSED ON THE TANKS AND PUMPS TO STOP THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE FIRE DEPARTENT SPRAYED THE RELEASED PRODUCT WITH WATER TO CONTROL THE VAPORS.  A RESULTING POOL OF CORROSIVE LIQUID COVERED AN AREA OF ABOUT 10,000 SQUARE FEET BETWEEN THE RAIL CAR AND RAILWAY'S MAIN TRACK. A PUMP TRUCK WAS UTILIZED TO RECOVER LIQUID FROM THE POLING AREA. ESTIMATES FOR THE EVACUATION AND INJURY COUNTS WERE OBTAINED FROM THE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT OFFICE AND RAILWAY PERSONNEL AT THE SCENE.  COST ESTIMATES FOR DAMAGE AND REMEDIATION AREA NOT AVAILABLE.

CAR INSPECTORS PERFORMING INBOUND TRAIN YARD INSPECTION DETECTED A FAINT SMELL OF AMMONIA NEAR THIS CAR.  ATSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE LIQUID LINE VALVE TO BE ONE-HALF TURN OPEN AND LIQUID LINE VALVE PLUG TO BE THREE TURNS LOOSE.  THESE CONDITIONS WERE CORRECTED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

CONTAMINATED SNOW WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.

column168: ONE DRUM FELL OFF OF THE BARREL TRUCK.  BARREL WAS UPRIGHTED AND SOLVENT EVAPORATED.  BARREL WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  TERMINAL CONDUCTED A SAFETY MEETING WITH ALL THE DOCKWORKERS.

ONE DRUM WAS ACCIDENTALLY PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT WHILE TRANSFERRING THE DRUMS.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED UPSIDE DOWN AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT.  THE DRUM WAS THEN PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON OVERPACK.  THE DRUM WAS MARKED, LABELED, AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  AT DESTINATION, THE CHECKER WAS UNLOADING THE FREIGHT AND THE SMELL THAT HAD REMAINED CAUSED HIM TO BECOME DIZZY AND HIS EYES WATERY.  HE WAS TAKEN TO THE COMPANY DOCTOR AS A PRECAUTION.  ACCORDING TO THE PHYSICIAN HE CHECKED OUT OKAY AND WAS ALLOWED TO RETURN TO WORK.  THE DRUM IS PRESENTLY SITTING IN OS&D AND IS AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

DRUM STARTED TO LEAK DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BUNG/RELIEF VALVE WAS FAULTY.  THE SMALL SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  ALL THE HF DRUMS ARE BEING INSPECTED AT RINCHEM AND J.T. BAKER.  J.T. BAKER IS CONDUCTING AN INVESTIGATION OF THEIR VALVE SYSTEMS.

WHEN LOADING, THE EXTERNAL VALVE STARTED TO VIBRATE.  THE VIBRATION CAUSED THE PACKING NUT TO LOOSEN ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK BY.  LOADING WAS STOPPED TO RETIGHTEN PACKING NUT AND LOADING RESUMED WITHOUT A PROBLEM. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT WAS LOST AND THIS AMOUNT EVAPORATED WITHIN 2 MINUTES.

column168: DAVE KENDRA WAS CALLED TO THE EAST PRIMARY, BAY 143, TO CLEAN UP A LIQUID DAMAGE.  AFTER CONSULTING DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN LIQUIDS, HE PROCEEDED TO IDENTIFY THE DAMAGE.  THERE WAS NOT A 5 PLY NOR A HAZARDOUS DIAMOND. HE ADDED CLAY BASED ABSORBENT AND HAD JIM JOHNSON ASSIST HIM WHILE I TYPED REPORT. DISPOSED THROUGH DMP PROCEDURES.

column168: THE SAVANNAH INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT EMPLOYEE LEFT A VALVE PARTIALLY CLOSED ALLOWING FUEL INTO TWO TANKS INSTEAD OF THE DESIGNATED TANK, CAUSING OVERFILL OF TANK WITH APPROXIMATELY 450 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  MR BILLY MATHIS OF SAVANNAH INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT HAS ACCEPTED FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SPILL AND THE CLEAN-UP.

DRIVER NOTICED FUEL COMING OUT OF VENTING PIPE AND STOPPED HIS UNLOADING PROCESS IMMEDIATELY.  APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO TWO EMPLOYEES CARS.  VEHICLES WERE WASHED BY CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEES AND SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY KENAN DRIVER AND CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEES WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DIESEL FUEL FITTING CAME LOOSE FROM THE TANK FILL PIPE DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED VALVES TO STOP PRODUCT FLOW. SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY KENAN DRIVER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DRIVER WAS MAKINNG ROUTINE DELIVERY.  HOOKUP WAS PROPER PROCEDURES OK.  HE FAILED TO OPEN VALVE AT CUSTOMERS SIGHT.  A MISTAKE THAT CAUSED A 3" DISCHARGE HOSE TO SEPARATE FROM ITS METAL CONNECTOR, HITTING DRIVER IN RIGHT LEG, RESULTING IN A SPILL.  DRIVER WAS AT VALVE AND CLOSED IMMEDIATELY.  DRIVER WAS REMINDED OF SAFETY PROCEDURES FOR UNLOADING PRODUCT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: DOCK WORKER WAS UNLOADING TRAILER 261188 FROM GREENSBORO TERMINAL WHEN HE NOTICED THAT CARTON WAS DAMP, TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED TO ISOLATION AREA AND EMERGENCY NUMBER WAS PHONED.  MSDS WAS SECURED FROM SHIPPER AND ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICE WAS CALLED TO HANDLE CLEANUP.  CLEANUP WAS ACCOMPLIASHED BY ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND DAMAGED CARTON WAS PLACED IN OVERPACK AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES ACCORDING TO ALL STATE AND FEDERAL LAWS.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: DOCKMAN OPENED BACK DOOR OF TRAILER & SAW THE DAMAGED CARTON.  HE NOTICED HIS SUPERVISOR.  WE LOOKED AT BILL TO ASSESS HAZARDOUS CLASS, THEN SPREAD A NEUTRALIZER ON THE SPILL, ADDED A DRYING AGENT, THEN SCOOPED ALL MATERIALS INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  ORIGIN TERMINAL WAS NOTIFIED OF POOR LOADING.
DRUM NOTED LEAKING WHEN UNLOADING.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM TO PREVENT SPILLING ON THE FLOOR.  FREIGHT WAS THEN OFFERED TO CONSIGNEE IN SALVAGE PAIL.
ONE, 55 GALLON PUNCTURED WITH A DRUM TRUCK.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND SENT BACK TO SHIPPER PER DENNIS ESPOSITO WITH FINE ORGANICS CORP.

column168: SHOP PERSONNEL DISCOVERED LEAKING DRUM WHEN THEY NOTICED PAINT DRIPPING OUT THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER WHEN IT CAME OFF THE ROAD FROM THE ORIGIN TERMINAL.  THEY OPENED THE DOOR AND FOUND THE PUNCTURED DRUM ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THEY IMMEDIATELY OFF-LOADED THE DRUM AND LAID IT ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING.  EVIDENTLY, DURING TRANSIT, ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT STRUCK THE DRUM AND CAUSED A SMALL PUNCTURE ON THE BACKSIDE OF THE DRUM.  DRUM TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD LOAD DRUM ON OUTBOUND TRAILERS IN A WAY WHICH WILL PREVENT DRUMS FROM BEING DAMAGED IN TRANSIT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: TRAILER WAS CLOSED CHICAGO TO HOUSTON.  DRIVER NOTICED LEAK AND CAME INTO LITTLE ROCK.  THE LEAK CAME FROM A CARTON THAT HAD BEEN LOADED ON ITS SIDE AND IT LEAKED THROUGH THE CAP.  THE TOTAL SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF TWO SKIDS OF 46 CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING ONE BAG WITH A CAP AS A LID.  THE ONE CARTON THAT LEAKED AND THREE OTHERS THAT WERE SOAKED WERE PLACED IN SPILL KITS.  THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED IN A SPILL KIT ALSO. THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT IS BEING SENT TO DESTINATION AS IT IS A RETURN TO THE SHIPPER SHIPMENT.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: SHIPMENT WAS BLOCKED IN WITH DECKING BARS.  A FEW CARTONS STILL CAME LOOSE AND FELL OFF THE PALLET.  WE CLEANED UP A SMALL SPILL WITH STAY DRY. BETTER BLOCKING WOULD PREVENT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/SPILLAGE OCCURRED.  THE PACKAGE WAS APPARENLTY DROPPED IN HANDLING CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE INNER CONTAINER WHICH WAS MADE OF GLASS.  THIS CAUSED A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY FOUR LITERS OF MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ALKALI, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE FREIGHT SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/SPILL WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PACKAGE HAD APPARENTLY BEEN DAMAGED IN TRANSIT AND WAS LEAKING PROFUSELY WHEN IT ARRIVED IN ATLANTA.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A FIVE VOLT CAR BATTERY CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY TWO LITER OF ALKALI.   THE BATTERY'S CASING HAD BEEN CRACKED AND THIS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE BATTERY.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS, LABELS, NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN ASSOCIATION WITH THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS PART OF A SIX LOT WITH THE OTHERS BEING ALREADY IN THE DELIVERY CYCLE AND OUT TO THE DESTINATION STATION FOR DELIVERY TO THE RECIPIENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE F.A.A. IN ATLANTA WAS NOTIFIED FOR INVESTIGATION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED.  THE PLASTIC DRUM WAS ISOLATED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL THAT THERE WAS LEAKAGE AROUND THE FRICTION SCREW ON LID AT THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  APPARENTLY THE LID WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY AND THIS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY THREE OUNCES OF THE CONTAINER.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE AND WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS DISCOVERED.  THE DRUM WAS ISOLATED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL THAT THE SEAL AT THE TOP OF THE DRUM HAD FAILED AND THIS ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF MATERIAL TO STAND ON THE LID.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE AND THE METAL DRUM WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURED.  THE PACKAGE WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING. THIS CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE INNER CONTAINER THAT RESULTED IN THE SPILLAGE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE ABD THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

APPARENTLY THE PACKAGE FELL OUT OF THE CART AND WAS RUN OVER BY A FORKLIFT.  THIS DAMAGED THE INNER CONTANER ENOUGH SO THAT APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED. column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: CP RAIL TRAIN NO 226-6 HEADING EAST NEAR POWERSVILLE, MO. WENT INTO EMERGENCY AND WHEN TRAIN CREW WAS INSPECTING THEIR TRAIN, FOUND 8 CARLOADS OF BOMBS DERAILED AND 29 BOMBS SPILLED OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  2 OF THE CARS WERE OFF LOADED INTO TRAILERS AT THE SITE AND 6 WERE TRANSFERRED INTO TRAILER AT SEWAL, IA AND RUBBERED TO BILLED DESTINATION.  2 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THEIR HOMES DURING THE INITIAL STAGES OF RESPONSE BUT, LATER ALLOWED TO RETURN.  THERE IS NO CLEAN UP NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE OCCURED.  THE SEAL ON THE CAP OF THE INNER PLASTIC CONTAINER APPARENTLY FAILED DURING TRANSPORT.  THERE WERE NO OTHER SIGNS THAT THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN DROPPED OR OTHERWISE MISHANDLED.  THIS ALLOWED A RELEASE OF SIX OUNCES OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY, 0835 HOURS, SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 24, 1996, DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS AT CONRAILS AVON IN RAIL YARD, TANK CAR GATX 47668 (ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., (HOT PETROLEUM ASPHALT) WAS STRUCK BY EMPTY GONDOLA CAR 570250.  TANK CAR GATX 47668 SUSTAINED A TEAR IN THE A END, RIGHT SIDE OF THE HEAD OF THE TANK MEASURING APPROXIMATELY 12 INCHES BY 3/4 INCHES.  LEAK WAS PLUGGED UTILIZING WOODEN PLUGS AND CAR MOVED TO CAP SHOP WHERE CONTENTS TRANSFERRED BY CONTRATOR INTO RAIL CAR UTLX 70895 AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP ACCOMPLISHED BY PRIVATE CONTRACTOR ON CONTRACT WITH CONRAIL.

PACKAGE WAS PART OF THE INBOUND FREIGHT LOAD AND WAS BEING UNLOADED TO BE PROCESSED FOR MORNING DELIVERY WHEN THE DAMAGE/SPILL WAS DISCOVERED.  THE INNER CONTAINER HAD APPARENTLY BEEN PUNCTURED IN TRANSIT AND THIS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 4-6 OUNCES OF THE MATERIAL FROM THE BOTTOM ON THE INNER CONTAINER WHICH WAS MADE OF PLASTIC.  LABELS ON THE INNER CONTAINER CLEARLY INDICATED THE MATERIAL AS ISOPROPANOL ALCOHOL.  THE PACKAGE DID NOT EXHIBIT ANY OTHER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS OR LABELS NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN ASSOCIATION WITH THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION.

AT APPROXIMAELY, 0440 HOURS, SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 3, 1996, RANK CAR TLDX 120075 (CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID) SLOWED WHILE TRAVELING THROUGH THE MASTER RETARDER AT THE CONRAIL RAIL FACILITY IN ELKHART, INDIANA.  CAR WAS STRUCK BY FASTER MOVING RAIL CAR WHICH CAUSE IMPACT STRONG ENOUGH TO ACTIVATE THE CAR'S SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE AND RUPTURE THE 100 LBS RATED RUPTURED DISK.  CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE. PERSONNEL REPRESENTING SHIPPER (DOVER CHEMICAL) RESPONDED TO THE RAIL YARD AND REPLACED THE BROKEN RUPTURE DISK.  CAR CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1730 HOURS, 2/3/96.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: TANK CAR WAS FOUND BY A TRAINYARD CARMAN WITH RELEASED PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATION AREA AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.  BUCKETS WERE PLACED UNDER THE CAR.  ATSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE RELEASE AND DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT WAS BEING RELEASED BY THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND MANWAY. ALL INDICATORS POINTED TO OVERFILLING.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR PRODUCT TO BE OFF-LOADED INTO A TANK TRUCK.  A TOTAL OF 2500 GALLONS WAS PUMPED FROM THE CAR.  WHEN THE MANWAY WAS OPENED, PRODUCT WAS LEVEL WITH THE HOUSING UPPER LID.  DUE TO THE 78 DEGREE F. AMBIENT TEMPERATURE, AS COMPARED TO THE 58 DEGREE F. LOADING (PRODUCT) TEMPERATURE, THERMAL EXPANSION CANNOT BE EXCLUDED FROM THE POTENTIAL CONTRIBUTORS.

column72: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: AT APPROX 1530 HRS THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 22, 1996, TANK CAR DUPX20048 (RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINING METHACRYLIC ACID, INHIBITED) WAS DISCOVERED IMPROPERLY SECURED DURING HAZMAT AUDIT CONDUCTED BY CONRAIL'S HAZMAT TEAM PERSONNEL AT THE CONRAIL DICKINSON YARD FACILITY DICKINSON, WV.  INSPECTION BY CONRAIL'S HAZMAT PERSONNEL REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT EYEBOLTS NOT APPLIED (8 OF 8) AND MANWAY COVER GASKET BROKEN, PROTECTIVE HOUSING OF THE LOADING AND UNLOADING VALVES NOT SECURED.  CONRAIL'S HAZMAT TEAM PERSONNEL ARRANGED TO HAVE TRACK SECURED AND TO MAKE NECESSARY SECUREMENT. THE MANWAY GASKET WAS OVERLAPPED PRIOR TO SECUREMENT, THE MANWAY COVER AND PROTECTIVE HOUSING SECURED.  RAIL CAR RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION UPON CORRECTIVE SECUREMENT.
TANK OVER-FLOWED WHILE LOADING.

OUR VEHICLE WAS DONE UNLOADING AT CUSTOMER'S TANK.  UNHOOKED HOSE FROM OUR TRAILER AND WAS ATTEMPTING TO CLIMB OVER DIKE TO CHECK TANK VALVE AND SOME BACK PRESSURE DEVELOPED AND HOSE ON GROUND OUTSIDE DIKE RELEASED OIL ONTO THE GROUND.  CUSTOMER CLEANED UP OIL AND PLACED PRODUCT INTO A ROLL OVER CONTAINER.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT INTO A CUSTOMERS TANK - OVERFILLED THE TANK. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED BY SNOW.  ALL CONTAMINATED SNOW WAS REMOVED FROM AREA. GROUND WAS FROZEN SOLID.  NO PRODUCT ENTERED GROUND.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TRANSFERRING PRODUCT FROM CUSTOMER TANK TO OUR CARGO TANK & CARGO TANK OVERFLOWED.  THERE WAS TOO MUCH PRODUCT.  MISCALCULATED.  PRODUCT WASHED DOWN INTO CUSTOMER SYSTEM.
1 DRUM FELL OVER IN TRANSIT, PUNCTURED, SOME MATERIAL LEAKED.  INCIDENT DISCOVERED WHEN TRAILER DOORS WERE OPENED FOR THE PURPOSE OF UNLOADING.
AT TIME OF DELIVERY THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM FAILED (CRACKED) AND ALL THE CONTENTS SPILLED IN THE TRUCK.  IN ORDER TO AVOID THIS IN FUTURE, THE PLASTIC DRUM SHOULD BE MADE OF THICKER PLASTIC.

column42: HYDRAZINE, AQUEOUS SOLUTION, WITH NOT MORE THAN 37 PERCENT HYDRAZINE, BY MASS
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS LOADED BY THE PLANT IN LAKE CHARLES AND THEN TRANSPORTED DIRECTLY TO OUR TERMINAL IN LITTLE ROCK, AR.  UPON OPENING THE TRAILER AT THE DOCK, THEY FOUND SOME OF THE PRODUCT HAD LEAKED AND THE FUMES WERE BAD.  THEY CLOSED THE TRAILER IMMEDIATELY AND ISOLATED IT ON THE YARD. OLIN CHEMICALS EMERGENCY HOTLINE WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND EMERGENCY INSTRUCTIONS WERE RECEIVED.  THEY CONTRACTED FERGUSTON - HARBOR TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  FERGUSTON - HARBORS FOUND ONE DRUM THAT HAD A GASH AT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AND ALL OF THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT.  THE MAJORITY OF THE MATERIAL LEAKED INTO THE TRAILER, WITH ONLY A MINOR AMOUNT ON THE GROUND.  THEY RECOOPED THE DRUM AND CLEANED UP THE PRODUCT.  THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED BACK TO ABF.  WE NOTIFIED THE U.S. COAST GUARD A THE APPROX. 4:00 P.M.  AFTER THE CLEAN-UP CREW DETERMINED HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS LOST. THE SHIPPER IS AWARE OF THE PROBLEMS AND WILL ADDRESS THIS ISSUE WITH THE PLANT INVOLVED.

I WAS CALLED TO DOOR 3A, ORANGE BELT FOR A LEAKING HAZARD.  USING PROPER PPE I IDENTIFIED THE HAZARD AND USING THE DECISION TREE I CLEANED UP THE SPILL FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID ACCORDING TO RESPONSE SHEET.  AFTER CLEANUP DAMAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP AREA.  SECOND RESPONDER DONNED SCBA TO PROCESS SPEED.  DRY/SOLUSORB AND CARDBOARD.

WHILE ENROUTE, DRIVER WAS CHECKING LOAD AND NOTICED SOME PRODUCT WAS RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  THE DRIVER SPREAD SOME ABSORB ALL MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER NOTICED A BAD GASKET WHEN CHECKING THE DRUM. DRIVER WAS APPROX. 1 HOUR FROM THE GENERATOR SO HE RETURNED.  THE GENERATOR OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND CLEANED UP THE PRODUCT FROM THE FLOOR OF CONTAINMENT PAN.

AEROSOL CAN WAS DROPPED, CAUSING PUNCTURE TO CAN, ENTIRE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT.  SATURATING CARDBOARD, CONTAMINATED PORTION DISPOSED OF THROUGH MALLIN CROFT PROCEDURE.  REMAINING PORTION RECORDED AS DAMAGE RETURNED TO SHIPPER.
PACKAGE HAD CANS WITH LOOSE CAPS, WHICH LEAKED OUT ONTO CARDBOARD SATURATING PACKAGE.  CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD DISPOSED OF THROUGH MALLIN CROFT PROCEDURE.  THE REST SHIPPED OUT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: CARGO ARRIVED IN SLC ON FLIGHTS 377/18TH AND 377/19TH.  TWO (2) OF THE BOXES WERE DAMP WITH FROM LEAKAGE OF CONTENTS.  THESE BOXES WERE OPENED TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF DAMAGE TO THE SHIPPED GOODS.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT NO LEAK PROOF SEALED LINERS WERE USED AS PART OF THE PACKAGING TO PREVENT ANY LEAKAGE.  THIS REQUIRED BY IATA PACKAGING NOTE 800 THE SHIPMENT WAS TERMINATED IN SLC AND GIVEN TO KUEHNE AND NAGEL, THE SHIPPERS AGENT.

I WAS CALLED TO DOVER BELT, DONNED PPE, FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, USED CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, USED SODIUM DICARB PROCESSED THRU DMP PROGRAM. CLEANED UP SODIUM BICARB.

FIRE STARTED IN THE TRAILER WHILE THE UNIT WAS IN ROUTE.  THE FIRE CONSUMED ALL 11 BOXES OF THIS SHIPMENT.
THE CAP TO THE DRUM WAS NOT ON AND THE LIQUID HAD LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR AND ONTO SOME OTHER FREIGHT.  RESIDUE RECOUPED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
ONE DRUM PUNCTURED WTH DRUM HAD CART, DRUM TURNED UPSIDE DOWN TO STOP LEAKAGE, OIL DRY USED TO CLEAN UP SPILL.  FREIGHT RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

THE PAIL SLIPPED OFF THE DRUM DOLY WHICH CAUSED THE DRUM DOLY TO STRIKE THE PAIL WHICH CAUSED THE LEAK.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AN PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER.

HE ENTERRED THETRALER AND RAN INTO THE PEICE OF WOOD CAUSING ONE BOX OF POSION TO GET PUNCTURED.  TWO BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED IN THE PROCESS. column14: 5 MILE NE OF LIBBY ON HWY
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS OPERATING OUR TRUCK #1971 ( 1975 KENWORTH W900).  #1971 WAS PULLING TRAILER #3072 (A 1994 CAT 1000 KW GENRATOR) AND PUP TRAILER #3079 (A 1973 FRUEHAUF 5,200 GALLON TANKER). OUR DRIVER HAD LEFT HIGHWAY 37 AND WAS ON RAINY CREEK ROAD.  HE HAD TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 300 YARDS UP THE ROAD WHEN THE TRUCK SPUN OUT, DESPITE HAVING TIRE CHAINS ON THE REAR DUCALS.  THE DUALS ACTUALLY DUG INTO THE ROADWAY APPROX 2 INCHES.  THE ROAD WAS SNOW AND ICE PACKED.  OUR DRIVER RADIOED OUR 988 FRONT END LOADER(FEL) OPERATOR, WHO WAS WORKING AT OUT GRAVEL PIT ONE MILE FURTHER UP RAINY CREEK.  OUR DRIVER WAITED FROM TEN TO FIFTEEN MINUTES FOR THE FEL TO ARRIVE.  WHEN THE FEL ARRIVED, OUR DRIVER SET THE AIR BRAKES AND THE PARKING BRAKE.  HE THEN GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK TO HOOK THE WIRE ROPE SLING ON THE FEL TO THE TRUCK.  HE DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS ANY WAY TO HOOK THE SLING TO THE TRUCK.  OUR DRIVER THEN WENT TO THE FEL OPERATOR AND ASKED HIM TO RADIO FOR THE RATED CHAINS.  ABOUT THAT TIME, THEY BOTH HEARD A NOISE AND LOOKED AT THE TRUCK AND TRAILERS.  THE WHOLE UNIT WAS SLIDING BACKWARDS DOWN THE ROAD.  THE UNIT SLID APPROXIMATELY 80 YARDS BEFORE THE TANKER JACK-KNIFED AND WENT OVER THE NORTH SIDE OF THE ROAD DOWN A 15 TO 20 FOOT EMBANKMENT.  THE TANKER PULLED THE GEN SET TRAILER AND TRUCK WITH IT.  ALL THREE VEHICLES CAME TO A STOP AT THE BOTTOM OF THE EMBANKMENT. THE TANKER WAS RUPTURED BY THE GEN SET TRAILER, AND BEGAN LEAKING FUEL INTO RAINY CREEK FIVE FEET AWAY.

column168: TEO DRUMS WERE LOADED AT JACKSON, MS TERMINAL.  THEY WERE PLACED ON A PALLET THAT WAS 3' x 3'.  THE DRUMS WERE NOT SECURED WITH BANDING.  WHEN THEY ARRIVED IN DOTHAN, THEY WERE ON THEIR SIDE AND ONE HAD LEAKED ABOUT 15 GALLONS.  WE RECOUPED INTO SALVAGE DRUM.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: DRUM LEAKED AT THE BUND WHEN IT WAS A 45 DGREE ANGLE DURING UNLOADING AFTER TRANSPORT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE BUNG VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE AND THE DRUM WAS SENT BACK TO SHIPPER FOR TESTING.  A MORE STRINGENT DRUM INSPECTION POLICY HAS BEEN IMPLEMENTED AT RICHEM.

WHILE UNLOADING A 8 CYLINDER OF OXYGEN, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 3 WERE VENTING OFF EXCESS GASES.  THIS WAS CAUSED IN PART BY OVERFILL BY SHIPPER, AMBIENT AIR TEMPERATURE AND THE MOVEMENT OF THE CYLINDER BY ROAD. THESE CYLINDERS WERE SEPARATED FROM ALL OTHER FREIGHT AND PLACED ON AN EMPTY TRAILER TO ALLOW FOR VENTING ASPER THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.  THE MEMPHIS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM INSPECTED THE LEAKING CYLINDERS AND CONFERRED WITH THE SHIPPERS INSTRUCTIONS TO ALLOW TO VENT UNTIL THEY SEALED THEMSELVES.  THREE CYLINDERS CONTINUED TO VENT FOR THESE DAYS AND NIGHTS IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA AND SEALED THEMSELVES AFTER THE INTERNAL PRESSURE HAD DROPPED. ALL EIGHT CYLINDERS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AS PER THE SHIPPER'S REQUEST.

column168: INFORMATION FROM LOCAL POLICE, AS WELL AS A MAINTENANCE EMPLOYEE, INDICATED A LPG RELEASE FROM THIS CAR.  THE TRAIN WAS TOPPED AWAY FROM A POPULATED AREA; HOWEVER, US HIGHWAY 60 WAS PARALLEL TO THE TRACK.  BOTH HIGHWAY AND RAIL TRAFFIC WAS INTERRUPTED FROM 2040 2/18 TO 0100 2/19 WHEN TEMPORARY REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE CAR.  ATSF RESPONDERS WERE ASSISTED BY THE CONSIGNEE'S RESPONSE TEAM AND A RESPONDER FROM HOECHST CELANESE'S PLANT AT KINGS MILL.  THE ASSESSMENT VALVE.  THE FAILED SPRING PERMITTED A CONTINUOUS RELEASE OF PRODUCT. AFTER THE SAFETY VALVE WAS TEMPORARILY SECURED, THE CAR WAS MOVED TO A SIDING FOR REPAIR FACILITY FOR REPAIRS AND TESTING.  ITEM 23(E) INDICATES TRAIN DELAY AND CREWS RESULTING FROM THIS EVENT.

THE TRAINMASTER NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEIR HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BLIND PHLANGE BOLTED ONTO THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTLET EXTENSION PIPE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT STOPPED THE LEAK BY CLOSING THE VALVE (THE VALVE HAND WAS NOT SECURED) AND TIGHTENNG THE BOLTS ON THE BLIND PHLANGE.  THE CAR THEIR ABLE TO BE RELEASED.

PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED TO STOP THE PRODUCT RELEASE.  A REPLACEMENT BOLT WAS INSTALLED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE SEALING SURFACES.  THE FRANGIBLE DISK WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE INTACT.  SHIPPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR REMOVAL/ NEUTRALIZATION OF RELEASED PRODUCT THROUGH AN ENVIRONMENAL CONTRACTOR.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO SPOT AT A LOCAL INDUSTRY.

THE IMPETUS FOR THIS REPORT WAS THE OUTCOME OF AN INVESTIGATION BY THE FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTION TEAM THAT WAS CONCLUDED ON JUNE 5, 1996. THIS CAR WAS REPORTED BY A SWITCH CREW TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN A RECEIVING YARD TRACK.  IT WAS SWITCHED OUT OF THE TRACK AND TO THE SAFE HAVEN DRIP TRACK.  LEAKAGE WAS REPORTED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AT THE END.  THIS IS A THREE COMPARTMENT CAR, SO THE EXACT COMPARTMENT IS NOT KNOWN). APPROPRIATE ATSF HAZMAT RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED OF ITS CONDITION, SO THERE WAS NEITHER AN ASSESSMENT OR A REPAIR MADE.  AS THE CAR HAD NOT BEEN BACK ORDERED, IT WAS APPARENTLY PULLED FROM THE DRIP TRACK ACCOUNT, IT WAS PRESUMED TO HAVE BEEN REPAIRED AND RELEASED.  FOLLOWING SWITCHING INTO THE YARD, IT WAS INTERCHANGED FOR LOCAL DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. DUE TO THE LACK OF COMMUNICATION CONCERNING THE CAR'S LEAKING CONDITION IN ACCORDANCE WITH ESTABLISHED GUIDELINES, THE CAR WAS NOT REPORTED AS HAVING SUSTAINED AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE.  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO ALERT ALL PERSONNEL OF THIS OCCURENCE.  IN ADDITION, A TRAINING PROGRAM SPECIFICALLY FOR SUPERVISORS WILL DEBUT THIS SUMMER.  IT REITERATES THE CORRECT HANDLING OF LEAKING SHIPMENTS IN A VARIETY OF SITUATIONS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO THE UST AT A CONVENIENCE STORE. THE UST WAS EQUIPPED WITH AN EXTRA ACCESS PORT AT THE OPPOSITE END OF THE TANK FROM WHERE THE FILL AND VAPOR FITTINGS ARE. AS OUR DRIVER NEARED COMPLETION OF THE DELIVERY, GAS CAME OUT OF THE EXTRA UST PORT AT THE OPPOSITE END OF THE TANK. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT ICE IN THE WELL AROUND THE CAP FOR THE EXTRA PORT HAD FORCED THE CAP OFF THE PIPE ALLOWING GAS TO ESCAPE. THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 95-14295. THE ICE WAS REMOVED FROM THE WELL AND A NEW CAP INSTALLED TO PREVENT FUTURE PROBLEMS.

column168: ON MONDAY, FEBRUARY 19,  1996 OUR DRIVER TERRY SWAGGERTY WAS IN ROUTE TO WILLIAMS PIPELINE, MILFORD, IOWA WITH A LOAD OF DENATURED ALCOHOL.  HE FAILED TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE AS HE ENTERED A SHARP CURVE LOCATED 2 MILES NORTH OF CYLINDER, IOWA ON HWY 18.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER BOTH WERE DAMAGED AND ENDED UP ON THE YARD OF A FARM OWNED BY LLOYD MOSIER.  THE PALO ALTO SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT, IOWA D.O.T., AND THE D.N.R., ALL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE TRAILER LEAKED 3605 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON TO THE GROUND THROUGH 2 DOMES LOCATED ON THE TOP OF THE TANKER. WE THEN SENT ANOTHER UNIT TO THE SCENE AND TRANSFERED THE REMAINING GALLONS TO THIS TRAILER AND DELIVERED TO WILLIAMS PIPELINE CLEAR LAKE.  WE FOLLOWED THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT AND THE CLEAN UP AT THE SITE LOCATION. WE HAVE SINCE STRESSED TO ALL OF OUR DRIVER'S THE NEED TO USE CAUTION ON ALL ROADS, UNDER ALL CONDITIONS.

I, KAREN NICHOLS/ HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COODRINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177  INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT AT OUR SORT FACILITY OF THE SAME ADDRESS.  THE SHIPMENT HAD NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS AFFIXED, NOR DID A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A PLASTIC EXPRESS PACK ENVELOPE.  INSIDE THE EXPRESS ENVELOPE I FOUND 10 LIPSTICKS AND 8 X 13 ML GLASS BOTTLES OF NAIL ENAMEL.  2 OF THE 8 WERE BROKEN AND THEIR ENTIRE CONTENTS LOST.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED.  THERE WAS ALSO A SMALL CARDBOARD BOX INSIDE THE PLASTIC EXPRESS PACK THAT THE ABOVE PRODUCTS MIGHT HAVE BEEN LOADED IN ORIGINALLY.  THE COSMETICS AND CARDBOARD BOX WERE INSIDE A PAPER ENVELOPE INSIDE THE PLASTIC EXPRESS PACK.  THIS AND KEY PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.  SIGNATURE OF PERSON FILING REPORT.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT DAVIDSON WATER ON 2/16/96 AT 2230 TO DELIVER A LOAD OF CAUSTIC SODA.  DUE TO THE FACT THAT THERE WAS CONSTRUCTION EQUIPMENT IN FRONT OF THE UNLOADING AREA THE DRIVER, ALAN COX, HAD TO RUN APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET OF HOSE FROM THE TRAILER TO THE CUSTOMERS TANK.  THE OPERATOR AT THE SITE THEN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO UNLOAD INTO A BASIN AND PROCEEDED TO LIFT THE LID OFF AND BEGAN OFF-LOADING.  AFTER SIGNING THE PAPERWORK HE LEFT AND LET THE DRIVER FINISH UNLOADING.  THE DRIVER THEN FINISHED THE JOB AND RETRIEVED THE PAPERWORK AFTER THE OPERATOR HAD SIGNED STATING HE HAD RECEIVED THE PRODUCT IN GOOD ORDER.  ON MONDAY 2/17/96 WE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM DAVIDSON WATER STATING THAT WE HAD UNLOADED THE PRODUCT INTO A BASIN WHICH CONTAINED THE ACTUAL PRODUCT TANK.  AFTER QUESTIONING THE DRIVER HE STATED THAT HE WAS AWARE OF ANY CONNECTIONS WITHIN THE BASIN AND COULD NOT SEE ANY DUE TO DARKNESS.  HE ALSO STATED THAT THE OPERATOR DID NOT MENTION ANY CONNECTIONS WITHIN THE BASIN.  CONT. ON BACK AT THAT PONT THE GREENSBORO TERMINAL MANAGER (CHRIS STEELY) ALONG WITH KEN ROWE WENT TO INVESTIGATE.  THE CAUSTIC WHICHW AS IN THE BASKIN WAS THEN PUMPED BACK OUT AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BORIC ACID.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: VII & VIII ABOVE:  NO PACKAGE FAILURE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  OUR DRIVER DISPATCHED TO LEWIS COUNTY HOSPITAL WITH 7,000 GALLONS OF #2 HEATING OIL AS DIRECTED BY SEARS OIL COMPANY.  DRIVER ARRIVED AT HOSPITAL AT 0400 AND HAD TO WAIT FOR HOSPITAL MAINTENANCE EMPLOYEE TO UNLOCK THE FILL CAP FOR THE TANK OUR DRIVER WAS TO FILL.  THE STORAGE TANKS ARE BELOW GROUND BEHIND THE BUILDING AND NOT VISIBLE TO THE UNLOADING DRIVER.  UPON HIS ARRIVAL, THE HOSPITAL EMPLOYEE UNLOCKED THE FILL CAP FOR ONE OF THE TANKS AND INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO UNLOAD INTO THAT TANK.  HOSPITAL EMPLOYEE WAS SUPPOSED TO MONITOR DELIVERY AT THE TANKS.  OUR DRIVER FINISHED THE DELIVERY AT 0530 AND LEFT THE LOCATION.  SOMETIME AFTER OUR DRIVER LEFT A HOSPITAL EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED THAT THE LOAD HAD BEEN DELIVERED INTO THE WRONG TANK AND ABOUT 5,500 GALLONS HAD GONE OUT THE VENT PIPE INTO A STORM DRAIN THAT EMPTIES INTO MILL CREEK.  THE HOSPITAL CALLED NEW YORK STATE DEP OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WHO ARRANGED FOR THE CLEANUP. THEIR REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 95-14556. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE HOSPITAL EMPLOYEE THAT UNLOCKED THE FILL CAP HAD NOT MONITORED THE DELIVERY AT THE TANKS.

COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY ROBERT SCHUT, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT A TANK CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL AT YERMO.  TANK CAR CELX 5133, MOVING IN THE HKYR-01, NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAIN, ARRIVED YERMO AT 1000 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 7 1996.  LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP AREA AND RUNNING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE TANK CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS LEFT IN PLACE AND THE IMMEDIATE AREA WAS KEPT ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO FACILITY AND FOUND THE TANK WAS STILL LEAKING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR AT AN APPROXIMATE RATE OF 1/2 GALLON PER MINUTE.  THE WAYBILL INFORMATION SHOWED THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR TO BE ETHYL METHYL KETONE, UN1193, HOWEVER, THE TANK CAR WAS PLACARDED UN1224. USING THE EMERGENCY TELEPHONE NUMBER FROM THE WAYBILL, CONTACTED LARRY GROCHOLSKI, SECURITY, CELANESE, EDMONTON, ALBERTA, CANADA, WHO STATED HE WOULD HAVE SOME CONTACT THE RAILROAD.  WHILE WAITING FOR THE RETURN CALL, MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE TANK CAR IN AN EFFORT TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  UPON CLIMBING TO THE TOP OF THE CAR, OBSERVED PRODUCT TO BE LEAKING FROM THE CLOSING EDGE (OPPOSITE OF THE HINGE) OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WHERE THE GASKET SEPERATES THE PLATE FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  ALL EIGHT OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHT, WHICH INDICATED A BAD MANWAY COVER PLATE SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHT, WHICH INDICATED A BAD MANWAY COVER PLATE SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHT, WHICH INDICATED A BAD MANWAY GASKET.  THE PROTECTIVE COVER HOUSING FOR THE VALVES WAS OPENED AFTER REMOVING SECURITY SEAL CNR93W10544910 FROM THE SEAL PIN.  CHECKING THE CLOSURE PLUG FOR THE AIR LINE FOUND THE PLUG ONLY FINGER TIGHT, HOWEVER, THE BALL VALVE WAS CLOSED, AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE.  THE PLUG WAS REMOVED AND THE BALL VALVE ON THE AIR LINE WAS CRACKED OPEN TO REDUCE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE OF THE TANK CAR.  THERE WAS VERY LITTLE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AS THE VALVE ONLY INDICATED A SMALL AMOUNT OF RELEASE FOR LESS THAN TWO MINUTES.  ONCE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS REDUCED, THE FLOW FROM THE MANWAY CEASED.  THE MANWAY BOLT SECURITY SEAL CNR93W10544910 WAS REMOVED IN ORDER TO LOOSEN THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS AND OPEN THE COVER PLATE.  UPON OPENING THE COVER PLATE, OBSERVED PRODUCT TO THE TOP OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS LOOSE AND PULLED AWAY FROM THE COVER PLATE.  INSPECTION OF THE GASKET REVEALED SIGNS OF IT BEING CROSSED BETWEEN THE COVER PLATE AND NOZZLE.  THERE WERE NUMEROUS CRACKS AND TEARS ON THE RUBBER GASKET, INDICATING IT HAD BEEN IN SERVICE FOR SOME TIME. THE COVER PLATE WAS LEFT PROPPED OPEN UTILIZING ONE OF THE SWING BOLTS, AND THEN COVERED WITH A PLASTIC SHEET TO PREVENT ANY FOREIGN CONTAMINATION OF THE LADING.  MANAGER COOPER WAS CONTACTED BY REX CAREY AND DOUG SMITH, BOTH REGIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATORS, CELANESE, EDMONTON, CANADA. BOTH WERE APPRISED OF THE SITUATION AND THAT THE EASIEST SOLUTION WOULD BE TO EFFECT A LOAD REDUCTION OF T

1050 HRS. ON 2/8/96, SR. SPECIAL AGENT T.J. BOUDREAX WHILE MAKING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS IN THE AVONDALE YARD FOUND TANK CAR NATX 245 WITH AN ODOR OF PRODUCT CLOSE TO THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER.  AGENT BOUDREAX REMOVED CABLE SEAL CYTEC 128288 AND WHEN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS OPENED THERE WAS A SLIGHT TRACE OF PRODUCT LOCATED AT THE BASE OF THE LIQUID VALVE.  THE PRODUCT QUICKLY DISIPATED AS THE WIND FANNED IT.  AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO TIGHTEN THE VALVE WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS.  TANK CAR NATX 245 WAS IN TRAIN AVLI 08 AND AGENT BOUDREAUX REQUESTED THE CAR BE CUT OUT TO A SAFE LOCATION TO BE REPAIRED.  AGENT BOUDERAUX NOTIFIED CYTEC INDUSTRIES, SUPERINTENDENT, TRANSPORTATION SPECIALIST, EMERGENCY RESPONSE CHRIS M. FRILOUX.  AT 1645 HRS. ON2/8/96 TANK CAR NATX 245 WAS SPOTTED ON THE AVONDALE YARD SCALE TRACK AS FRILOUX & BLANE BRAUD ARRIVED.  FRILOUX & BRAUD REMOVED ALL THE VALVES, CLEANED THE FITTINGS AND APPLIED TEFLON PIPE TAPE TO ALL OF THE FITTINGS.  THEY REPLACED THE LIQUID VALVE AND REAPPLIED THE VAPOR AND VACUUM RELIEF VALVES.  AT 1735 HRS. ON 2/8/96, AGENT BOUDREAUX CONTACTED YARDMASTER BAILEY AND RELEASED TANK CAR NATX 245 TO CONTINUE MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO FURTHER INCIDENTS WERE REPORTED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE MAKING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT THE UNION PACIFIC YARD AT LIVONIA, LOUISANA, FRA HAZ-MAT INSPECTOR JAMES DUNCAN OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR CCBX 1083.  UPRR DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATION, MIKE CAMPBELL WAS NOTIFIED AND HAD THE CAR SET OUT AND ISOLATED.  UPRR MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, DAVE MEYERS, WAS NOTIFIED AND PLACED A SMALL METAL WASH TUB UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE LEAKAGE.  ADDITIONAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO UPRR SPECIAL AGENT HAZ/MAT T.J. BOUBREAUX, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY T.M. ROBINSON AND UNION CARBIDE.  MR. JACK PALLAZOO AND MR. MILTON FRY, TRANSPORTATION TECHNICIANS FROM UNION CARBIDE AT TAFT, LA. RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  FRY AND PALLAZZO WERE ABLE TO BE TO TIGHTEN THE NUTS THAT SECURED THE VALVE TO THE FLANGE AND THIS SLOWED THE LEAKAGE. THEY DECIDED THAT IT WOULD BE BEST TO TRANSFER THE LOAD BEFORE RETURNING THE CAR TO TAFT.  CAR UTLX 640899 WERE SPOTTED TO SET OUT TRACK #97 TO FACILITATE THE TRANSFER. UNION CARBIDE ARRANGED FOR ENTERPRISE TRUCKING TO SUPPLY A TRUCK, WITH PUMP, AND A CARGO TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS WERE PLACED IN THE CARGO TANK AND THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WAS PLACED INTO UTLX 640899.  THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED WITH OUT INCIDENT.  BOTH TANK CARS AND THE CARGO TANK WILL BE SHIPPED TO UNION CARBIDE AT TAFT, LA.

column168: ON 020896AT APPROXIMATELY 445PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, CHARON DINKINS, THAT TWO CREW MEMBERS HAD SMELLED AN ODOR COMING FROM A CAR IN TRACK 206.  THE MAN REPORTED THE VAPORS IRRITATED THEIR EYES AND MADE THEM "LIGHT HEADED."  REEDER INSPECTED THE TRAK AND FOUND THE ODOR COMING FROM THE ABOVE CAR.  AN INSPECTION OF THECAR FOUND ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE TIGHT, HOWEVER, A SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE MANWAY COVER GASKET.  REEDER TIGHTENED THE BOLTS BUT WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK. RATHER THAN MAKE A GASKET, REEDER ASKED THE SHIPPER TO BRING A NEW GASKET TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL THE TEAM DETERMINED THE CAR HAD TOO MUCH PRESSURE AND THAT VENTING IT TO THE ATMOSPHERE WOULD NOT BE DESIRABLE. USING POWER TOOLS, THE TEAM WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

column62: Over-pressurized; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: JEFF STATON, EMPLOYEE AND VEHICLE OPERATOR O.E. MEYER COMPANY WAS INVOLVED IN A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  JEFF WAS DRIVING EAST ON NEW WASHINGTON ROAD BETWEEN STATE ROUTE 4 AND STATE ROUTE 19 JUST NORTH OF LYKENS, OHIO IN CRAWFORD COUNTY AT ABOUT 11:00 AM. WHEN THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED. APPARENTLY, JEFF'S VEHICLE CAUGHT THE DIRT AND GRAVEL SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  DUE TO THE EXTREMELY WET WEATHER CONDITIONS, THE SHOULDER COULD NOT SUSTAIN THE WEIGHT OF THE VEHICLE AND LOAD.  THE VEHICLE CONTINUED TO TRAVEL FOR ABOUT 600 FEET WITH TIRES ON THE RIGHT SIDE OFF THE ROAD.  JEFF ATTEMPTED TO BRING THE TRUCK BACK UP ON THE ROAD WHEN HIS VEHICLE WAS COMPLETELY OFF THE ROAD.  AS A RESULT OF THIS ACTION, THE VEHICLE ROLLED OVER, DUMPED THE LOAD, AND RIGHTED ITSELF.  THERE WERE 136 CYLINDERS IN THE SHIPMENT.  ALL BUT 5 OF THIS NUMBER ARE DESIGNED AND WERE PROVIDED WITH VALVE CAPS.  THE REMAINDER WERE ARL'S (CONTAIN REFRIGERATED LIQUID). OF THESE 5, 2 NITROGEN ARLS VENTED (RELEASED THEIR PRODUCT IN A GASEOUS FORM).  NITROGEN IN AN INERT GAS UNDER PRESSURE.  THE PICTURE ENCLOSED IN THIS REPORT DEPICTS THIS ACTION.  WITHIN MINUTES OF THE ACCIDENT, JEFF GOT OUT OF THE VEHICLE AND CALLED THE CRAWFORD COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT FROM AN NEARBY RESIDENCE.  THE CRAWFORD COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT, LYKENS VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE EMS ALL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  JEFF SUFFERED SOME INJURIES AND WAS TAKEN TO BUCYRUS COMMUNITY HOSPITAL.  HE WAS TESTED FOR DRUGS AND ALCOHOL AND BOTH TESTS SHOWED UP NEGATIVE.  HE RETURNED TO WORK THE FOLLOWING DAY.  AFTER CALLING THE SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT, JEFF CALLED ART KUNS, GALION DIVISION MANAGER WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED CARSON VAN NESS, COMPLIANCE OFFICER AT O.E. MEYER COMPANY HEADQUARTERS IN SANDUSKY OHIO.  CARSON VAN NESS DROVE DOWN TO THE SIGHT AND WAS ON THE SCENE WITHIN AN HOUR OF THE ACCIDENT.  HE LOCATED THE MANIFEST AND ASSURED THE LOCAL RESPONDERS THAT THERE WERE NOT ANY POISONOUS GASES OR A SERIOUS HEALTH THREAT INVOLVED WITH THE DISSIPATING GAS VENTING FROM THE CYLINDERS.  PICTURES WERE ALSO TAKEN FOR DOCUMENTATION PURPOSES.  AT ABOUT 12:30, A TRUCK FROM SANDUSKY ARRIVED ON THE SCENE TO START THE REMOVAL OF THE CYLINDERS.  THE ROAD WAS CLOSED DOWN UNTIL APPOXIMATELY 4:00PM.  CARSON VAN NESS RETURNED TO SANDUSKY AND CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND SPOKE TO A MS. SHORES AT APPROXIMATELY 3:45PM.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT CITED FOR THE ACCIDENT.  THE DAMAGED CYLINDERS ARE CURRENTLY BEING TESTED FOR INTERNAL PRESSURE. PICTURES OF THE ACCIDENT WERE SHOWN TO ALL OF THE DRIVERS IN THE COMPANY AND THEIR THOUGHTS AND IDEAS WERE SOLICITED.  AS A RESULT MANY OF THE DRIVERS WERE GIVEN A STRONG DOSE OF REALITY AND REAFFIRMATION ON THE IMPORTANCE OF SAFETY TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  IT WAS AGREED THAT IF A SIMILAR SITUATION WAS TO OCCUR, THE DRIVER SHOULD NOT ATTEMPT TO GET BACK ON THE ROAD.  EMPHASIS WAS PLACED ON THE FACT THAT CALLING A TOW TRUCK IS PREFERABLE TO THE DAMAGE, CLEANUP, THE RETRIEVAL OF PROPERTY AND EQUIPMENT.

AT 1600 HRS. ON 2/15/96, SR. SPECIAL AGENT T.J. BOUDREAUX RECEIVED A CALL FROM RAMP SUPERVISOR BILL MAAS WHO ADVISED THAT A BULKTAINER WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM AN AREA AT THE BOTTOM REAR OUTLET VALVE.  AT 1610 HRS. ON 2/15/96, AGENT BOUDREAUX ARRIVED AT THE UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT PIGGYBACK FACILITY AND MET WITH MAAS WHO STATED THE FOLLOWING:  *UPMF DRIVER FRANK MEADOWS PICKED UP BULKTAINER UPTU 430040 AT NALCO CHEMICAL CO. IN GARYVILLE, LA.  *MEADOWS ARRIVED AT THE UPMF PIGGYBACK FACILITY AT 1510 HRS. ON 2/15/96.  *AT 1540 HRS. ON 2/15/96 AS THE BULKTAINER WAS BEING LOADED PIGGYPACKER DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE BULKTAINER WAS LEAKING AT THE AREA OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  *GOFFNER PLACED THE BULKTAINER ON BLOCKS AND HAD PLASTIC BUCKETS PLACED UNDER THE DRIPPING PRODUCT.  AGENT BOUDREAUX INSPECTED THE BULKTAINER AND NOTED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM A DEAD END FLANGE JUST FORWARD OF THE BOTTOM REAR OUTLET VALVE. AGENT BOUDREAUX NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AS SUPERVISOR MAAS NOTIFIED THE JEFFERSON PARISH 911 CENTER TO CONTACT JEFFERSON PARISH EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS.  MAAS ALSO NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, NALCO CHEMICAL CO. AND SPOKE WITH DALE VICNAIR.  VICNAIR INFORMED MAAS THAT HE WOULD DISPATCH HIS EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO THE UPMF PIGGYBACK FACILITY. LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZMAT RESPONDER RONNIE MAUEAUX ARRIVED AND REPORTED INCIDENT ON ITEM LSP 96-0647.  JEFFERSON PARISH HAZMAT & NINE MILE POINT VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENTS ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY SPECIALIST LUKE PIRANO ALSO ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. BULKTAINER UPTU 430040 WAS AGAIN INSPECTED BY ALL HAZMAT RESPONDERS AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LADING WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED.  LSP MAYEAUX CONTACTED NALCO'S EVERETT GAUTHIER AND ADVISED HIM OF THE DECISION TO TRANSFER THE BULKTAINS PRODUCT.  MAYEAUX THEN REQUESTED THAT A SUITABLE TANK TRAILER OR BULKTAINER BE DISPTACHED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT.  NALCO CHEMICAL HAZMAT RESPONDER WILLIE PARANIO ARRIVED AND WAS ADVISED OF THE DECISION TO TRANSFER THE LADING IN THE BULKTAIN.  AFTER PARANIO INSPECTED THE BULKTAINER HE AGREEDED WITH THAT DECISION. LSP MAYEAUX CONDUCTED A SAFETY BRIEFING AND THE TRANSFER OPERATION BEGAN BY UTILIZING THE PUMP ON THE SCHNEIDER TANK TRUCK.  AT 2245 HRS. TRUCK TRANSPORTED THE EMPTY BULKTAINER UPTU 430040 BACK TO NALCO CHEM. TO CLEAN IT AND RETURN IT TO THE MPMF'S WESTWEGO TERMINAL. column168: DURING INSPECTION, FRA INSPECTOR J. CONNELLY FOUND GATX 85892 WITH A SLOSH LEAK IN THE AREA OF THE MANWAY LID.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED.  THE CAR WAS MOVED BACK TO ITS LOADING STATION WITH THE PERMISSION OF MR. CONNELLY, WHERE THE MANWAY LID WAS SECURED AND THE CAR CLEANED OF RESIDUE.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH NOTED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF TANK TANK CAR MKT 100406. column168: A UNION PACIFIC SWITCH CREW WORKING IN THE UPRR SOUTH OMAHA YARD OBSERVED AND REPORTED POSSIBLE LEAKAGE FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR GATX 18390 WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY BROUGHT TO REST AND ISOLATED, AWAITING INSPECTION.  UNION PACIFIC SPECIAL AGENT - HAZARDOUS MATERIALS KEN DECHANT INSPECTED THE CAR AT 10:55 HRS SAME DATE, FINDING THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD FAILED.  VENT ASSEMBLY WAS NOT EQUIPPED WITH BAFFLES TO REDUCE PRODUCT SURGE.  DECHANT REPLACED THE DISC WITH AN IDENTICAL 100# BS&B STAINLESS STEEL/TEFLON DISC.  IT WAS NOTED AT THAT TIME THAT ONE OF THE FOUR DISC RETAINER BOLTS HAD BEEN BROKEN OFF PRIOR TO INSPECTION.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE FOUND SECURE.  CAR WAS RELEASED AT 11:45 HRS FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION, A DISTANCE OF APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE.  NO SPILLAGE WAS OBSERVED.  SHIPPER WAS FURNISHED DETAILS OF THIS INCIDENT, AND WILL ARRANGE FOR REPAIR OF VENT ASSEMBLEY.  CHEMTREC FILE #42345.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY CREWS REPORTING PRODUCT WHICH WAS NOTED DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET ON CAR SCMX2103 WHICH HAD ARRIVED KANSAS CITY, NEFF YARD TRACK 103, TRAIN FWKC.  ON GROUND INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE CAR WAS A TWO COMPARTMENT CAR WITH THE LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF THE "A" END COMPARTMENT AT A RATE OF 9 DROPS PER MINUTE.  CAR EQUIPPED WITH A "JAMESBURY 4" INTERNAL PORT BALL VALVE".  THE METAL PIN KEEPER HAD BEEN WELDED ON THE JACKET AT A POINT WHERE WHEN THE OPERATING HANDLE STOP HIT THE PIN KEEPER, THE VALVE WAS JUST CLOSED.  THE SECUREMENT PIN WAS EXTRA LONG WHICH ALLOWED THE VALVE HANDLE TO TO VIBRATE TOWARD THE OPEN POSITION THUS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SEEP BY THE VALVE SEAT. THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET WAS BRITTLE AND GROVED.  REPLACED GASKET AND SECURED CLOSURE.  DISCUSSED THE INCIDENT WITH MR. DAVE MASHINSKI WHO INDICATED THEY WOULD INSPECT THE CAR PRIOR TO RE-LOADING.

column168: A REPORT OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AND EVACUATION AT GRANDVIEW TX WAS REPORTED AT NOON ON A RADIO NEWSCAST.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET CALLED JOHNSON SHERIFF TO CONFIRM AND ADVISE.  ONCE CONFIRMED, SHE HEADED TO THE SCENE. (NEWS REPORTERS ARRIVED WITH POLICE, FIRST ON SCENE).  THE HOFW 08 WAS ON THE MAINLINE IN GRANDVIEW,TX WAITING FOR TRAFFIC TO CLEAR.  WHILE THERE, AN MERCAPTAN-LIKE ODOR WAS NOTED BY AN ADJACENT BUSINESS, UNIVERSAL FOREST PRODUCTS.  WHEN THE ODOR INTENSIFIED, THEY CALLED THE POLICE.  THERE WERE RESIDUE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (BENZENE, TOLUENE) CARS, FLAMMABLE LIQUID CARS AND CORROSIVE CARS IN THE ODOR AREA.  THE GRANDVIEW FIRE DEPT EVACUATED THE DOWNWIND AREA WHICH INCLUDED THE LUMBER YARD (150), A SCHOOL (900) AND 7-10 HOUSES.  ESTIMATED TOTAL WAS 1100 PERSONS.  THE 2 STREETS WHICH RUN ADJACENT AND PARALLEL TO THE AREA WERE CLOSED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC. THE WIND WAS BLOWING W-SW AT 8-10 MPH.  MS. ROQUET MET UPRR MTO LARRY HOPKINS AT THE SCENE.  MS. ROQUET, WITH THE FIRE CHEIF, CHECKED THE CARS AND DETERMINED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 88169 (RESIDUE: LAST CONTIANED FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (BENZENE AND TOLUENE)) WAS LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE MANWAY.  MTO HOPKINS ADVISED AND COORDINATED WITH HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER TO MOVE THE CAR TO EGAN SIDING, 14 MILES NORTH.  THE CAR WOULD THEN BE IN A RURAL AREA AND REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  TRAIN TRAFFIC WAS CLEARED AND THE CAR WAS MOVED AT APPROX 1500 HRS TO EGAN.  CW (CHARLIE) HALL, BOE FIELD INSPECTOR HAZMAT WAS ON SCENE TO ASSIST.  FRA HAZMAT INSPECTORS WALT GIBSON AND PAUL KLIMAS WERE ALSO ON SCENE.  ONCE THE CAR WAS IN POSITION, THE PRESSURE WAS BLED OFF VIA THE AIR INLET AND THE MANWAY OPENED.  THE GASKET WAS INTACT, BUT BRITTLE.  GORTEX ROPE GASKET WAS APPLIED TO THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE COVER SECURED.  SEALS REXENE 280436/275610 WERE REMOVED TO AFFECT REPAIRS. REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AT 1850 HRS AND THE TRAIN PULLED OUT AT 1900 HRS. REXENE 915-333-7200 HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY CHEMTREC AND WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT AND CAR STATUS.  TNRCC SCOTT CARNEY 2142986171 WAS ALSO ON SCENE.

UPRR CAR FOREMAN KENNY AMOS FOUND TANK CAR UTLX 41028 LEAKING FROM THE TOP DURING YARD CHECK.  UPON INSPECTION, HE FOUND THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE LIQUID LINE.  THE LIQUID VALVE WAS 1/4 TO 1/2 OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS HAND TIGHT.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON A MINUTE, BUT WAS EVAPORATING BEFORE HITTING THE GROUND.  TEMPERATURE WAS IN THE 70'S. AFTER TIGHTENING THE FITTINGS, ALL OTHERS WERE CHECKED AND FOUND SECURE. SEAL # EPC13986 WAS REMOVED TO EFFECT REPAIRS.  SEAL #UPX556252 WAS APPLIED.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 1150 HOURS.  JOE BABER, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED 1600 HOURS, REPORT #41932.

UPEE CAR FOREMAN KENNY AMOS REPORTED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 41136 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  CAR WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 104.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THAT THE LIQUID VALVE WAS FULL OPEN.  THE PLUG WAS TIGHT, BUT PRODUCT WAS COMING OUT AND EVAPORATING BEFORE REACHING THE GROUND.  TEMPERATURE WAS IN THE 70'S.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE CHECKED AND FOUND SECURE.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 1100 HOURS.  SEAL #TCTRY CO. 98588 WAS REMOVED TO AFFECT REPAIRS.  SEAL # UPX556250 WAS APPLIED.  JOE BABER, CHEMTRE, WAS NOTIFIED, REPORT #41953.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION, STERLING YARDS, STERLING, COLORADO, NOTED PRODUCT COMING FROM MANWAY AREA. column168: CAR WAS DISCOVERED BY CARMAN AT UNION PACIFIC RAILYARD AT LIVONIA LOUISIAN TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK.  UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  THE LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM BENEATH THE MANWAY LID AND ALSO THE EDUCATION NOZZLE.  INSPECTION BY ROBINSON INDICATED THAT THE CAR WAS SHELL FULL AND THE LOAD NEEDED TO BE REDUCED.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED AT LIVONIA YARD.  THE SPILLAGE WAS EVAPORATING AS IT RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  UPON NOTIFICATION GRIME ARRANGED FOR CTL TRUCKING TO DISPATCHED A CARGO TANK TRUCK TO REDUCE THE LOAD.  MR. BILL BOSS OF CTL TRUCKING ARRIVED ON SCENE AT ABOUT 2145 HOURS WITH A CARGO TANK TRUCK.  ROBINSON AND BOSS TRANSFERRED ABOUT 500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR TO THE CARGO TANK.  BOTH THE CAR AND CARGO TANK WERE SECURE AT ABOUT 2310 HOURS.  WHEN THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT STARTED, PRODUCT WAS WITH IN ONE INCH OF THE TOP OF THE MANWAY  NOZZLE.  THE TRANSFER WAS STOPPED WHEN THE LIQUID LEVEL FELL BELOW THE TWO PERCENT INVERTED "T" BAR INSIDE THE TANK CAR.

UPRR CAR FOREMAN FRANK KRALICEK REPORTED THAT A TRAIN CREW NOTED TANK CAR UTLX 99445 IN BROWDER YARD TRACK 2, DALLAS, TX. HAD AN AMMONIA ODOR WHEN THEY PASSED IT.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM THE TOP AREA.  THE PRESSURE WAS GAUGED FROM THE SAMPLE LINE AND SHOWED 75 PSI.  UPEE SA-HM CARL ZERWECK RESPONDED TO ASSIST.  DALLAS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM WAS ADVISED AS INFORMATION. WHILE MS. ROQUET AND MR ZERWECK WERE CHECKING THE GAUGING DEVICE , VAPORS STARTED EMITTING FROM WHERE THE SAMPLE LINE TUBE THREADS INTO THE MANWAY COVER.  THE FITTING WAS TIGHTENED 1/2 TURN BEFORE THE TUBING STARTED TO STRESS.  THE LEAK DID NOT IMPROVE.  RATHER THAN POSSIBLY DAMAGE THE FITTING FURTHER, IT WAS DECIDED TO MAKE AN EMERGENCY MOVE TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR OFF-LOADING.  AT 0200 HOURS., 2-21-96, THERE WAS NO NOTICEABLE ODOR AT GROUND LEVEL.  THE PBP51-21 PLACED THE CAR LAST IN A CUT OF 10 CARS AND TOOK IT DIRECTLY TO STERRETT, TX.  IT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE AT 0900 HOURS., AND WAS IMMEDIATELY HOOKED UP AND OFF-LOADED.  JEFF BOTWINICK, CHEMTREC, WAS CALLED AT 2340 HRS., 2-20-96.

DURING THE PROCESS OF ROUTINE INSPECTION OF TANK CARS IN IVORY YARD, ST. LOUIS, SPECIALIST TUFTS NOTED A HISSING SOUND ON CAR  #UTLX130081.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION SPECIALIST TUFTS DETERMINED THAT SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY WAS LOOSE ALLOWING VENTING AND BYPASS TO DISC.  SPECIALIST TUFTS SECURED THE LOOSE BOLTS AND CHECKED FOR FURTHER LEAKS WITH SNOOP.  NO FURTHER LEAKS WERE NOTED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, KEN DALY, WAS NOTIFIED. CAR ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: ON 020696 AT APPROXIMATELY 10AM, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, BILL STREETY NOTIFIED MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING OIL FROM THE TOP.  A SWITCH MAN HAD BEEN SPLASHED BY THE OIL, BUT WAS NOT INJURED.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT TO AN ISOLATION TRACK. UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER FOUND ONE OF THE TWO SAFETY RELIEF VALVES WERE MISSING FROM THE DOME OF THE CAR.  THIS ALLOWED THE OIL TO SLOSH OUT WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE CONSIGNEE IS LOCATED A SHORT DISTANCE FROM THE YARD AND WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM.  THEY AGREED TO UNLOAD THE CAR INTO TRUCKS.
PETROMETER MALFUNCTIONED.

column168: THIS FREIGHT WAS BEING UNLOADED BY PETE KARABAN.  HE HEARD A HISSING NOISE COMING FROM ONE OF THE CYLINDERS.  THE SAFETY CAP WAS STILL IN PLACE, SO HE COULDN'T GET TO THE VALVE.  I CALLED CONSOLIDATED WASTE INDUSTRIES. GREGORY EMELE CAME OUT AND CHECKED INTO THE SITUATION AND SAID THE CYLINDER WAS IN FACT EMPTY NOW.  SINCE THE SAFETY CAP WAS STILL IN PLACE HE WONDERED IF THE VALVES WERE DEFECTIVE.  WE SENT THE SHIPMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR INSPECTION OF THE VALVES.
